## 5. Session Lifecycle Changes

### Skill materialization before session creation

With SurrealDB bucket storage, materialization reads raw files from the bucket and writes them to the sandbox agent's filesystem. No parse/reserialize — the original SKILL.md is written byte-for-byte.

```typescript
// session-lifecycle.ts — in assignTask(), after worktree creation

// 1. Resolve agent's active skills
const activeSkills = await resolveActiveSkills(input.surreal, identityRecord, workspaceRecord);

// 2. Read files from SurrealDB bucket and write to worktree
const skillDir = path.join(worktreePath, ".brain-skills");
await fs.mkdir(skillDir, { recursive: true });

for (const skill of activeSkills) {
  const dir = path.join(skillDir, skill.name);
  await fs.mkdir(dir, { recursive: true });

  // Read raw SKILL.md from bucket — preserved exactly as imported/authored
  const [skillMd] = await surreal.query<[Uint8Array]>(
    `<string> f"skills:/${skill.workspaceId}/${skill.name}/SKILL.md".get();`
  );
  await fs.writeFile(path.join(dir, "SKILL.md"), skillMd);

  // Materialize companion files (scripts, references) if present
  if (skill.companion_files?.length) {
    for (const file of skill.companion_files) {
      const filePath = path.join(dir, file);
      await fs.mkdir(path.dirname(filePath), { recursive: true });
      const [content] = await surreal.query<[Uint8Array]>(
        `<string> f"skills:/${skill.workspaceId}/${skill.name}/${file}".get();`,
      );
      await fs.writeFile(filePath, content);
    }
  }
}

// 3. Register with Sandbox Agent
if (activeSkills.length > 0) {
  await adapter.setSkillsConfig(worktreePath, "brain-skills", {
    sources: activeSkills.map(skill => ({
      type: "local",
      source: path.join(skillDir, skill.name),
    })),
  });
}

// 4. Register Brain MCP server (existing)
await adapter.setMcpConfig(worktreePath, "brain", { ... });

// 5. Create session (existing)
handle = await adapter.createSession({ ... });
```

### Brain-authored skills (SKILL.md generation)

For skills created through Brain's UI/API (not imported), Brain generates the SKILL.md from metadata fields and stores it in the bucket:

```typescript
async function createBrainSkill(surreal: Surreal, input: {
  name: string;
  description: string;
  instructions: string;  // Markdown body
  version: string;
  workspaceId: string;
  requiredTools: Array<{ name: string }>;
}): Promise<void> {
  const allowedTools = input.requiredTools.map(t => t.name).join(" ");
  const skillMd = [
    "---",
    `name: ${input.name}`,
    `description: ${input.description}`,
    ...(allowedTools ? [`allowed-tools: ${allowedTools}`] : []),
    "metadata:",
    `  brain-version: ${input.version}`,
    `  brain-workspace: ${input.workspaceId}`,
    "---",
    "",
    input.instructions,
    "",
  ].join("\n");

  // Store the generated SKILL.md in the bucket
  await surreal.query(
    `f"skills:/${input.workspaceId}/${input.name}/SKILL.md".put($content);`,
    { content: skillMd },
  );
}
```

Both imported and Brain-authored skills end up in the same bucket path. The materialization flow in the session lifecycle doesn't need to know the origin — it just reads from the bucket.

